            <div type="c">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>One Cent Reward!!!</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>One Cent Reward!!!</p>
                    <p>Ran away from the subscriber living near Jennings Gap, in this County, on the
                        7th of October, a negro Boy named</p>
                    <p>George Freeman,</p>
                    <p>aged about Twenty years--yellow complexion, very stout and healthy.</p>
                    <p>I will give the above reward if delivered to me, or secured so that I can get
                        him.</p>
                    <p>John Sanderson.</p>
                    <p>Nov 11--2t.</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Freeman</ln>
                        <fn>George</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Sanderson</ln>
                        <fn>John</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>George Freeman, age 23, with yellow complexion, very stout and healthy, ran
                    away from near Jennings Gap on October 7, 1864. John Sanderson offers a reward
                    of one cent for his return.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Negroes for Hire</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Someone has two African-American girls and two African-American boys to
                    hire out for the remainder of the year or for one year from the date of hiring.
                    The boys are 12 or 13 and 16 and can do any work on a farm or in a home. The
                    girls are 8 or 10 and 13 or 14, and the oldest is capable of doing housework.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
